Not to be confused with [Magnetic inductance](/Magnetic_inductance), which is an entirely different concept, though I can see how the terminology might confuse those not paying sufficient attention.

![Alternating electric current flows through the solenoid on the left, producing a changing magnetic field. This field causes, by electromagnetic induction, an electric current to flow in the wire loop on the right.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/Electromagnetic_induction.svg)
*Alternating electric current flows through the [solenoid](/Solenoid) on the left, producing a changing magnetic field. This field causes, by electromagnetic induction, an electric current to flow in the wire loop on the right.*

[Electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction), often referred to simply as [magnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction), is the rather fundamental phenomenon where a [voltage](/Voltage), specifically an [electromotive force (emf)](/Electromotive_force), is generated or "induced" across an [electrical conductor](/Electrical_conductor) when that conductor is subjected to a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) that is, for lack of a better term, *changing*. It's not enough for the field to simply exist; it must be in flux, dynamic, evolving. Static brilliance achieves nothing here.

The credit for first observing and documenting this rather significant principle generally falls to [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday) in 1831, a man whose empirical genius often outpaced the theoretical frameworks of his time. Later, the ever-meticulous [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell) provided the elegant mathematical description that solidified its place in physics, formulating what we now know as [Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction). The direction of the resulting induced field, a crucial detail for anyone actually trying to *use* this phenomenon, was subsequently explained by [Lenz's law](/Lenz%27s_law). [Faraday's law](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction) wasn't just a standalone curiosity; it was later generalized into the Maxwell–Faraday equation, which became one of the four foundational [Maxwell equations](/Maxwell%27s_equations) that underpin his comprehensive theory of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism). A truly impressive theoretical edifice built on a simple observation, if one is inclined to be impressed by such things.

The practical ramifications of [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction) are, unfortunately for those who prefer a simpler world, pervasive. It's the core principle behind countless electrical components, from humble [inductors](/Inductor) and sophisticated [transformers](/Transformer) to the very engines of modern society: [electric motors](/Electric_motor) and [generators](/Electric_generator). Without this principle, our world would be... well, significantly less electrified. Perhaps quieter, at least.

## History

![Faraday's experiment showing induction between coils of wire: The liquid battery (right) provides a current that flows through the small coil (A) , creating a magnetic field. When the coils are stationary, no current is induced. But when the small coil is moved in or out of the large coil (B) , the magnetic flux through the large coil changes, inducing a current which is detected by the galvanometer (G) .](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Faraday_induction_experiment.svg/300px-Faraday_induction_experiment.svg.png)
*Faraday's experiment showing induction between coils of wire: The liquid battery (right) provides a current that flows through the small coil (A) , creating a magnetic field. When the coils are stationary, no current is induced. But when the small coil is moved in or out of the large coil (B) , the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) through the large coil changes, inducing a current which is detected by the [galvanometer](/Galvanometer) (G).*

![A diagram of Faraday's iron ring apparatus. Change in the magnetic flux of the left coil induces a current in the right coil.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Faraday_ring.svg/200px-Faraday_ring.svg.png)
*A diagram of [Faraday's iron ring apparatus](/Faraday_ring). Change in the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) of the left coil induces a current in the right coil.*

[Electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction) was, as previously noted, first publicly revealed by [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday) in 1831. Curiously, and rather inconveniently for the neatness of history, it was independently stumbled upon by [Joseph Henry](/Joseph_Henry) in 1832. Much like two people inventing the same mediocre joke in different rooms, both arrived at the same profound discovery, though Faraday's findings saw earlier publication.

Faraday's inaugural experimental demonstration, a rather pivotal moment in scientific history, took place on August 29, 1831. His setup involved wrapping two distinct wires around opposite sides of an [iron ring](/Torus). This arrangement, for the historically minded, bears a striking resemblance to what we now recognize as a modern [toroidal transformer](/Toroidal_transformer). Driven by his existing insights into [electromagnets](/Electromagnet), Faraday theorized that if a [current](/Electric_current) were to commence flowing in one wire, some sort of "wave" – a rather poetic term for what was happening – would propagate through the [iron ring](/Torus) and manifest an [electrical effect](/Electricity) on the opposing side. To test this hypothesis, he connected one wire to a [galvanometer](/Galvanometer), an instrument designed to detect and measure electric current, and then observed its needle as he connected the *other* wire to a [battery](/Battery).

What he observed was not a continuous effect, as might have been initially hoped for, but a *transient current*. He dubbed this fleeting surge a "wave of electricity." Crucially, this wave appeared not only when he *connected* the wire to the [battery](/Battery), but also, and equally significantly, when he *disconnected* it. This transient behavior was the key. It wasn't the steady presence of a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) that induced the current, but rather the *change* in [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) that occurred during the moments of connection and disconnection. Within a mere two months, Faraday, a man clearly not content to rest on his laurels, unearthed several other manifestations of [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction). For instance, he noted similar transient currents when he rapidly moved a [bar magnet](/Magnet) in and out of a [coil of wires](/Inductor). Even more remarkably, he managed to generate a steady [direct current (DC)](/Direct_current) by rotating a [copper disk](/Copper) in close proximity to a [bar magnet](/Magnet), employing a sliding electrical lead – an ingenious device now famously known as [Faraday's disk](/Faraday%27s_disk).

Faraday, in his attempts to conceptualize and explain [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction), introduced the idea of "[lines of force](/Lines_of_force)." While intuitively powerful, these theoretical ideas were met with widespread skepticism by the scientific community of his era, largely because they lacked the rigorous mathematical formulation that was then, as now, the gold standard for scientific acceptance. One notable exception, however, was [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell). Maxwell, recognizing the profound insight embedded within Faraday's qualitative descriptions, utilized these very ideas as the bedrock for his quantitative, comprehensive theory of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism). In Maxwell's sophisticated model, the time-varying aspect that is so central to [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction) is precisely captured by a differential equation. This equation, which [Oliver Heaviside](/Oliver_Heaviside) later famously referred to as [Faraday's law](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction) (even though it diverged slightly from Faraday's original empirical formulation and notably didn't encompass motional emf), is the form universally recognized today as the Maxwell–Faraday equation, an indispensable component of the celebrated [Maxwell's equations](/Maxwell%27s_equations).

A few years later, in 1834, [Heinrich Lenz](/Heinrich_Lenz) contributed another essential piece to the puzzle, formulating the law that now bears his name. [Lenz's law](/Lenz%27s_law) provides the critical insight into the *direction* of the induced [electromotive force (emf)](/Electromotive_force) and the resulting [current](/Electric_current) generated by [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction), ensuring that the universe always opposes change. Because, apparently, it's just that contrary.

## Theory

### Faraday's law of induction and Lenz's law

*   Main article: [Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction)

![A solenoid: The longitudinal cross section of a solenoid with a constant electrical current (DC) running through it. The magnetic field lines are indicated, with their direction shown by arrows. The magnetic flux corresponds to the 'density of field lines'. The magnetic flux is thus densest in the middle of the solenoid, and weakest outside of it.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Solenoid_magnetic_field_lines.svg/300px-Solenoid_magnetic_field_lines.svg.png)
*The longitudinal cross section of a [solenoid](/Solenoid) with a constant electrical current ([DC](/Direct_current)) running through it. The [magnetic field lines](/Field_line) are indicated, with their direction shown by arrows. The [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) corresponds to the 'density of field lines'. The [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) is thus densest in the middle of the [solenoid](/Solenoid), and weakest outside of it.*

[Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction), in its most practical incarnation, hinges upon the concept of [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux), typically denoted as Φ B . This isn't just some abstract quantity; it quantifies the total [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) passing through a specific region of space that is enclosed by a wire loop. Think of it as counting how many invisible [magnetic field lines](/Field_line) are piercing through a given surface. The magnetic flux is rigorously defined by a [surface integral](/Surface_integral):

${\displaystyle \Phi _{\mathrm {B} }=\int _{\Sigma }\mathbf {B} \cdot d\mathbf {A} \,,}$

Here, d A represents an infinitesimally small element of the surface Σ, which is precisely the area enclosed by the wire loop. The term B denotes the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) vector at that point. The [dot product](/Dot_product) B · d A is not just mathematical flair; it signifies the infinitesimal amount of [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) passing perpendicularly through that tiny surface element. In simpler, more visual terms, as previously mentioned, the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) threading through the wire loop is directly proportional to the sheer number of [magnetic field lines](/Field_line) that happen to traverse the boundary of that loop. It's an inconveniently precise way of saying 'how much magnetism is going through this hole.'

The moment this [flux](/Magnetic_flux) through the enclosed surface decides to change, [Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction) dictates that the wire loop will, rather obligingly, acquire an [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (emf). This emf, for those who need a practical definition, is essentially the [voltage](/Voltage) you would measure if you were to snip the wire, creating an [open circuit](/Open-circuit_voltage), and then attach a [voltmeter](/Voltmeter) to the newly exposed leads. In a more fundamental sense, it represents the energy available from a unit charge that has completed one full traversal around the wire loop. The most widely accepted and utilized formulation of this law unequivocally states that the induced [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) in *any* closed circuit is precisely equal to the [rate of change](/Time_derivative) of the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) that is enclosed by that circuit. Mathematically, this elegant relationship is expressed as:

${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}=-{\frac {d\Phi _{\mathrm {B} }}{dt}}\,,}$

where ${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}}$ stands for the [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) and Φ B is, of course, the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux). Now, about that pesky negative sign: it's not merely a mathematical convention. It embodies the essence of [Lenz's law](/Lenz%27s_law), which dictates that an induced current will *always* flow in a direction that actively opposes the very change that produced it. It’s nature’s way of saying, “No, not like that.” To amplify the generated emf, because who wouldn't want more power, a common and rather effective strategy is to leverage [flux linkage](/Flux_linkage). This involves constructing a tightly wound [coil of wire](/Inductor), comprising N identical turns, each of which is permeated by the same [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux). The resulting total emf is then conveniently N times that of a single wire, a rather efficient multiplication.

${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}=-N{\frac {d\Phi _{\mathrm {B} }}{dt}}}$

Generating an emf through the variation of [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) through a wire loop's surface can be achieved through a few distinct methods, each presenting its own flavor of change:

*   **The [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) B itself changes:** This could be due to an [alternating magnetic field](/Alternating_current) that periodically reverses its direction and strength, or by simply moving a wire loop closer to or further from a [bar magnet](/Magnet) where the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) is inherently stronger or weaker, respectively. The field itself is dynamic relative to the loop.
*   **The wire loop is deformed, altering the surface Σ:** If the shape of the loop physically changes, expanding or contracting, the area it encloses also changes, thereby altering the total [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) passing through it, even if the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) itself remains constant.
*   **The orientation of the surface d A changes:** This is beautifully demonstrated by spinning a wire loop within a fixed, uniform [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field). As the loop rotates, the angle between the [magnetic field lines](/Field_line) and the surface normal changes, causing the effective [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) through the loop to vary sinusoidally.
*   **Any combination of the above:** Because nature, much like life, rarely keeps things simple, all these factors can conspire simultaneously to induce an emf.

### Maxwell–Faraday equation

*   See also: [Faraday's law of induction §&#160;Maxwell–Faraday equation](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction)

More generally, the relationship between the [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) ${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}}$ that manifests in a wire loop, which encircles a surface Σ, and the [electric field](/Electric_field) E present in the wire, is precisely given by a line integral:

${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}=\oint _{\partial \Sigma }\mathbf {E} \cdot d{\boldsymbol {\ell }}}$

Here, d ℓ represents an infinitesimal element of the contour, or boundary, of the surface Σ. When this expression for emf is combined with the fundamental definition of [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux):

${\displaystyle \Phi _{\mathrm {B} }=\int _{\Sigma }\mathbf {B} \cdot d\mathbf {A} \,,}$

we arrive at the integral form of the Maxwell–Faraday equation, a cornerstone of classical electrodynamics:

${\displaystyle \oint _{\partial \Sigma }\mathbf {E} \cdot d{\boldsymbol {\ell }}=-{\frac {d}{dt}}{\int _{\Sigma }\mathbf {B} \cdot d\mathbf {A} }\,.}$

This formidable equation is not just a theoretical exercise; it is one of the four [Maxwell's equations](/Maxwell%27s_equations), those sacred texts of [classical electromagnetism](/Classical_electromagnetism). Its presence underscores the utterly fundamental role that [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction) plays in describing how [electric](/Electric_field) and [magnetic fields](/Magnetic_field) interact and propagate throughout the universe. Without it, our understanding of light, radio waves, and perhaps even the very fabric of reality would be... incomplete.

### Faraday's law and relativity

It's worth noting, perhaps with a sigh, that [Faraday's law](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction) actually encompasses two distinct physical phenomena, which, for clarity, one might wish had been given entirely separate names. First, there's the *motional emf*, which arises from a [magnetic force](/Magnetic_force) acting upon a conductor that is physically in motion (a concept elegantly explained by the [Lorentz force](/Lorentz_force)). Second, there's the *transformer emf*, which is generated by an [electric force](/Electric_field) that directly results from a *changing* [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) (this is the aspect captured by the differential form of the Maxwell–Faraday equation). [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell) himself, with his characteristic attention to detail, drew specific attention to these separate physical phenomena back in 1861. This duality is often considered a rather unique example in the annals of physics, where such a foundational law is invoked to explain two phenomena that, on the surface, appear quite distinct.

However, the brilliant [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein), in one of his more insightful moments, observed that both these situations—a moving conductor in a static [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), and a static conductor in a changing [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field)—fundamentally boiled down to the same thing: a *relative movement* between a conductor and a [magnet](/Magnet). Crucially, the final outcome, the induced [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force), remained entirely unaffected by *which* of the two components was considered to be in motion. This profound realization, that the physics should be independent of the observer's frame of reference, was one of the pivotal intellectual pathways that eventually led him to develop the groundbreaking theory of [special relativity](/Special_relativity). So, a simple observation about wires and magnets somehow opened the door to reshaping our understanding of space and time. Unimpressive, perhaps, but undeniably effective.

