### Electrical generator

![Rectangular wire loop rotating at angular velocity ω in radially outward pointing magnetic field B of fixed magnitude. The circuit is completed by brushes making sliding contact with top and bottom discs, which have conducting rims. This is a simplified version of the drum generator .](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Drum_generator.svg/300px-Drum_generator.svg.png)
*Rectangular wire loop rotating at angular velocity ω in radially outward pointing [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) B of fixed magnitude. The circuit is completed by brushes making sliding contact with top and bottom discs, which have conducting rims. This is a simplified version of the [drum generator](/Drum_generator).*

*   Main article: [Electric generator](/Electric_generator)

The very heart of an [electrical generator](/Electrical_generator) lies in the emf induced by [Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction), a direct consequence of the relative motion between a circuit and a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field). This is how we convert brute-force mechanical energy into the convenient electrical form that powers our increasingly complicated lives. When a [permanent magnet](/Magnet) is moved relative to an [electrical conductor](/Electrical_conductor), or vice versa, an [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) is unfailingly created. Should this conductor be judiciously connected through an [electrical load](/Electrical_load), a [current](/Electric_current) will flow, thereby generating [electrical energy](/Electrical_energy) and achieving the rather miraculous conversion of the [mechanical energy](/Mechanical_energy) of motion into its electrical counterpart. The illustration above, for example, depicts a simplified [drum generator](/Drum_generator), a direct application of this principle. Another, historically significant, embodiment of this idea is [Faraday's disc](/Homopolar_generator), presented in a simplified schematic to the right.

In the case of the [Faraday's disc](/Homopolar_generator), a conductive disc is set into rotation within a uniform [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) that is oriented perpendicularly to the disc's plane. This rotation, through the action of the [Lorentz force](/Lorentz_force), compels a [current](/Electric_current) to flow radially along the disc's arms. To sustain this current, [mechanical work](/Mechanical_energy) must be continuously supplied. As this generated [current](/Electric_current) traverses the conducting rim of the disc, it, in turn, generates its own [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), a consequence of [Ampère's circuital law](/Amp%C3%A8re%27s_circuital_law) (labeled "induced B" in the diagram). This rim effectively transforms into an [electromagnet](/Electromagnet), and, in a perfect demonstration of [Lenz's law](/Lenz%27s_law), it generates a force that *resists* the disc's rotation. On the far side of the diagram, the return current flows from the rotating arm, through the far side of the rim, and back to the bottom brush. The B-field induced by this return current actively *opposes* the initial applied B-field, thereby tending to decrease the [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux) through that segment of the circuit, which, in turn, opposes the increase in [flux](/Magnetic_flux) caused by the rotation. Conversely, on the near side of the diagram, the return current flows from the rotating arm, through the near side of the rim, to the bottom brush. Here, the induced B-field *increases* the [flux](/Magnetic_flux) on this segment of the circuit, opposing the decrease in [flux](/Magnetic_flux) that would otherwise occur due to rotation. The energy meticulously expended to maintain the disc's motion, despite this reactive, opposing force, is precisely equivalent to the [electrical energy](/Electrical_energy) generated, plus, of course, any energy squandered due to mundane factors like [friction](/Friction), [Joule heating](/Joule_heating), and other inevitable inefficiencies. This elegant, albeit sometimes frustrating, dance of opposing forces is a fundamental characteristic common to all [generators](/Electric_generator) that undertake the conversion of [mechanical energy](/Mechanical_energy) into its electrical form.

### Electrical transformer

*   Main article: [Transformer](/Transformer)

When the [electric current](/Electric_current) flowing through a loop of wire undergoes a change, this dynamic current inevitably creates a corresponding, equally dynamic, [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field). Any second wire, positioned within the effective reach of this fluctuating [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), will consequently experience this change as a variation in its own coupled [magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux), represented by ${\displaystyle {\frac {d\Phi _{B}}{dt}}}$. As a direct and unavoidable consequence, an [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) is established within this second loop, aptly termed the *induced emf* or *transformer emf*. Should the two terminals of this second loop be connected across an [electrical load](/Electrical_load), a [current](/Electric_current) will then flow, allowing for the transfer of electrical power, often at a different [voltage](/Voltage) or [current](/Electric_current) level. It's a rather ingenious way to manipulate electricity without direct contact, if you think about it.

### Current clamp

![A current clamp](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Current_clamp.svg/200px-Current_clamp.svg.png)
*A [current clamp](/Current_clamp)*

*   Main article: [Current clamp](/Current_clamp)

A [current clamp](/Current_clamp) is, in essence, a specialized variant of a [transformer](/Transformer), distinguished by its split core. This core can be conveniently opened and then clipped around a wire or a [coil](/Inductor). Its primary function is twofold: either to precisely measure the [current](/Electric_current) flowing within that conductor, or, when operated in reverse, to induce a [voltage](/Voltage) within it. Unlike traditional instruments that necessitate direct electrical contact or the interruption of a circuit, the [current clamp](/Current_clamp) offers the distinct advantage of non-invasive measurement. It never makes electrical contact with the conductor, nor does it demand that the circuit be disconnected during its attachment. A surprisingly polite piece of equipment, for a change.

### Magnetic flow meter

*   Main article: [Magnetic flow meter](/Magnetic_flow_meter)

[Faraday's law](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction) also finds a rather practical application in the meticulous measurement of the flow rate of electrically conductive liquids and slurries. The instruments designed for this purpose are known, quite logically, as [magnetic flow meters](/Magnetic_flow_meter). The induced [voltage](/Voltage), denoted as ε, generated within a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) B when a conductive liquid moves through it at a velocity v, is given by a straightforward equation:

${\displaystyle {\mathcal {E}}=-B\ell v,}$

where ℓ represents the precise distance between the electrodes within the [magnetic flow meter](/Magnetic_flow_meter). This allows for accurate, non-intrusive measurement of liquid flow, a small mercy for those who have to deal with messy fluids.

### Eddy currents

*   Main article: [Eddy current](/Eddy_current)

When [electrical conductors](/Electrical_conductor) are put into motion through a steady [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), or conversely, when stationary conductors are subjected to a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) that is itself changing, a phenomenon known as [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) will inevitably be induced within them. These are essentially circular currents that flow in closed loops within planes oriented perpendicularly to the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field). They are named "eddy" because their swirling patterns often resemble the eddies seen in water. While [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) have genuinely useful applications, such as in [eddy current brakes](/Eddy_current_brake) (which offer smooth, contact-free deceleration) and [induction heating](/Induction_heating) systems (efficiently heating conductive materials), they are frequently an undesirable nuisance.

Specifically, [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) induced within the metallic [magnetic cores](/Magnetic_core) of [transformers](/Transformer), [AC motors](/AC_motor), and [generators](/Electric_generator) are particularly problematic. They dissipate valuable energy, which we rather uncreatively call [core losses](/Core_losses), primarily as heat due to the inherent [electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance_and_conductance) of the metal. To mitigate these wasteful effects, the cores of these devices employ a number of clever strategies:

*   **Laminated Cores:** For [electromagnets](/Electromagnet) and [transformers](/Transformer) operating at lower frequencies, particularly those handling [alternating current](/Alternating_current), the cores are rarely solid metal. Instead, they are meticulously constructed from stacks of thin metal sheets, known as [laminations](/Lamination), which are carefully separated by non-conductive coatings. These thin plates dramatically reduce the undesirable parasitic [eddy currents](/Eddy_current), a technique we'll delve into further below.
*   **Ferrite or Powdered Iron Cores:** At higher operating frequencies, [inductors](/Inductor) and [transformers](/Transformer) frequently utilize [magnetic cores](/Magnetic_core) crafted from non-conductive magnetic materials. These include [ferrite](/Ferrite_(magnet)) (a ceramic compound) or finely powdered iron particles held together by a resin binder. The non-conductive nature of these materials inherently limits the formation of [eddy currents](/Eddy_current).

### Electromagnet laminations

![Eddy currents occur when a solid metallic mass is rotated in a magnetic field, because the outer portion of the metal cuts more magnetic lines of force than the inner portion; hence the induced electromotive force is not uniform; this tends to cause electric currents between the points of greatest and least potential. Eddy currents consume a considerable amount of energy and often cause a harmful rise in temperature.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Eddy_currents_in_solid_metal_core_and_laminations.png/300px-Eddy_currents_in_solid_metal_core_and_laminations.png)
*Eddy currents occur when a solid metallic mass is rotated in a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), because the outer portion of the metal cuts more [magnetic lines of force](/Magnetic_lines_of_force) than the inner portion; hence the induced [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) is not uniform; this tends to cause electric currents between the points of greatest and least potential. Eddy currents consume a considerable amount of energy and often cause a harmful rise in temperature.*

The formation of [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) is particularly pronounced when a solid, continuous metallic mass is rotated within a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field). This is because the outer regions of the metal traverse and thus "cut" through a greater number of [magnetic lines of force](/Magnetic_lines_of_force) compared to the inner portions. Consequently, the induced [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) within the metal is not uniformly distributed. This differential in potential inevitably drives localized electric currents, or eddies, between areas of higher and lower potential. These [eddy currents](/Eddy_current), while a fascinating manifestation of physics, are notoriously inefficient, consuming a significant amount of energy which is then regrettably dissipated as heat. This can lead to a detrimental rise in temperature within the component, potentially impacting performance and lifespan.

The illustration above, for clarity, depicts only five [laminations](/Lamination) or plates, specifically to highlight how the [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) are subdivided and restricted. In real-world applications, particularly in high-performance [transformers](/Transformer) and motors, the number of individual laminations or punchings can range from a substantial 40 to 66 per inch (or approximately 16 to 26 per centimeter). This meticulous subdivision drastically reduces the undesirable parasitic [eddy current](/Eddy_current) losses, often bringing them down to a mere one percent of the total energy. While these plates *can* be deliberately separated by insulating materials, the induced [voltage](/Voltage) across adjacent laminations is typically so low that the naturally occurring rust or oxide coating on the surface of the plates is usually sufficient to effectively prevent any significant [current flow](/Electric_current) across the individual laminations. Nature provides its own insulation, sometimes.

![This is a rotor approximately 20&#160;mm in diameter from a DC motor used in a CD player. Note the laminations of the electromagnet pole pieces, used to limit parasitic inductive losses.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Laminated_motor_rotor_poles.jpg/200px-Laminated_motor_rotor_poles.jpg)
*This is a [rotor](/Rotor_(electric)) approximately 20&#160;mm in diameter from a [DC motor](/DC_motor) used in a [CD player](/CD_player). Note the [laminations](/Lamination) of the [electromagnet](/Electromagnet) pole pieces, used to limit parasitic inductive losses.*

### Parasitic induction within conductors

![In this illustration, a solid copper bar conductor on a rotating armature is just passing under the tip of the pole piece N of the field magnet. Note the uneven distribution of the lines of force across the copper bar. The magnetic field is more concentrated and thus stronger on the left edge of the copper bar (a,b) while the field is weaker on the right edge (c,d). Since the two edges of the bar move with the same velocity, this difference in field strength across the bar creates whorls or current eddies within the copper bar.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Eddy_currents_in_solid_conductor.png/300px-Eddy_currents_in_solid_conductor.png)
*In this illustration, a solid [copper](/Copper) bar [conductor](/Electrical_conductor) on a rotating [armature](/Rotor_(electric)) is just passing under the tip of the pole piece N of the field [magnet](/Magnet). Note the uneven distribution of the [lines of force](/Magnetic_lines_of_force) across the [copper](/Copper) bar. The [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) is more concentrated and thus stronger on the left edge of the [copper](/Copper) bar (a,b) while the field is weaker on the right edge (c,d). Since the two edges of the bar move with the same velocity, this difference in field strength across the bar creates whorls or [current eddies](/Eddy_current) within the [copper](/Copper) bar.*

For high-current, power-frequency devices, such as the formidable [electric motors](/Electric_motor), [generators](/Electric_generator), and [transformers](/Transformer) that keep our grids running, a common engineering solution to combat [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) within large, solid conductors is to employ multiple smaller conductors arranged in parallel. This strategic subdivision effectively breaks up the large-scale [eddy flows](/Eddy_current) that would otherwise form within a single, massive conductor. The very same principle is meticulously applied to [transformers](/Transformer) designed for operation at frequencies significantly higher than standard power frequencies—for instance, those found within [switch-mode power supplies](/Switch_mode_power_supply) or the [intermediate frequency](/Intermediate_frequency) coupling [transformers](/Transformer) integral to radio receivers. It's all about tricking the [eddy currents](/Eddy_current) into thinking there's no continuous path, a rather elegant deception.

